Problem Statement
======
Identify countries that showed an upward trend in engagement (comments) between December 2019 and January 2020. 
Engagement is measured by ranking countries based on total comment volume per month, where ties share the same rank without gaps.

SQL Approach
====
/*
 * Engagement Trend Analysis
 * Objective: Identify countries with improved engagement rankings month-over-month.
 */

WITH user_comments_count AS (
    -- Calculate total comments per country, per month
    SELECT 
        u.country,
        DATE_FORMAT(c.created_at, "%Y-%M") AS yr_mon,
        SUM(c.number_of_comments) AS total_comments
    FROM fb_comments_count c
    INNER JOIN fb_active_users u ON c.user_id = u.user_id
    GROUP BY 1, 2
),
ranking AS (
    -- Assign dense rank to countries within each month
    SELECT 
        country,
        yr_mon,
        DENSE_RANK() OVER (PARTITION BY yr_mon ORDER BY total_comments DESC) AS ranknum
    FROM user_comments_count
    WHERE yr_mon IN ("2019-December", "2020-January")
)
-- Compare performance: R1 (Dec) vs R2 (Jan)
SELECT 
    r1.country
FROM ranking r1
JOIN ranking r2 ON r1.country = r2.country
WHERE r1.yr_mon = "2019-December" 
  AND r2.yr_mon = "2020-January"
  AND r1.ranknum > r2.ranknum;


Engineering Notes & Interview Framing
====
1. Why DENSE_RANK()?
The prompt specifically required that countries with the same total share the same rank and that the "next rank should increase by one."

ROW_NUMBER() would have forced unique, arbitrary rankings on ties.

RANK() would have skipped numbers (e.g., if two countries were tied for 1st, the next country would be 3rd).

DENSE_RANK() is the correct choice here as it preserves tie-grouping while keeping the sequence consecutive (1, 1, 2...).

2. Self-Join Logic
=====
The join effectively creates a temporal state machine. 
By anchoring the join to specific strings ("2019-December" and "2020-January"), 
I isolate the exact transition the product team is interested in. 
The condition r1.ranknum > r2.ranknum translates the business requirement of an "improved rank" into a simple mathematical inequality 
(e.g., moving from 5th place to 2nd place).

3. Handling Nulls and Coverage
======
In this implementation, the INNER JOIN ensures that we only evaluate countries that were active (had comments) in both months.
This prevents "newly active" countries from skewing the improvement metrics, as they wouldn't have a valid comparison point in the December dataset.

This query demonstrates mastery of Window Functions for comparative analysis and the ability to map complex business rules to efficient relational set operations.
